      'One of the most important concepts in stressed asset investing is the gap between acquisition cost and replacement cost. The wider this gap, the larger your margin of safety.',
      'What Is Replacement Cost?',
      'Replacement cost is the total expenditure to recreate the asset at today’s prices: current land value, approvals and clearances, construction at today’s rates, financing costs, and marketing expenses. It represents the theoretical floor value of the asset.',
      'The Discount in Distressed Acquisitions',
      'In NCLT resolutions, assets are frequently acquired at 40 to 60 percent of replacement cost. This discount exists because the seller is in distress, the asset carries perceived risks, the buyer pool is smaller, and creditor losses are factored in. This creates a substantial margin of safety.',
      'Why Replacement Cost Matters for Returns',
      'If you acquire at 40 percent below replacement cost and successfully complete the project, you do not need market appreciation to generate returns. Converting a distressed project into a deliverable asset creates value equal to the discount. Any market appreciation is additional upside.',
